The '''Suburban Rail Loop''' ('''SRL''') is a [[rapid transit]] system currently under construction in [[Melbourne]], the capital of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and second largest city of [[Australia]]. The system is divided into three distinct sections (counterclockwise from southeast): '''SRL East''', '''SRL North''' and '''SRL West''', connected by [[Melbourne Airport Rail]] between the North and West sections.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/projects/suburban-rail-loop/about|title=About SRL|website=Victoria's Big Build|publisher=[[Victoria State Government]]|accessdate=2025-09-08}}</ref> The two main sections, [[Suburban Rail Loop East|SRL East]] and SRL North, are designed to form a single {{cvt|60|km}} [[automatic train operation|fully automated]] underground [[circle route|orbital metro line]] through the city's densely populated middle suburbs, with 13 stations between [[Cheltenham, Victoria|Cheltenham]] and [[Melbourne Airport]] connecting eight existing [[railways in Melbourne|Melbourne rail lines]] and three major [[universities in Australia#Universities in Australia|university campuses]].<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |date=26 October 2021 |title=Business and Investment Case |url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/projects/suburban-rail-loop/srl-north |access-date=24 October 2024 |website=Victoria’s Big Build |language=en}}</ref>

The SRL is a key part of Victoria's "Big Build" [[infrastructure]] initiative first proposed by the [[Andrews Government]], aiming to make Melbourne the second Australian city (after [[Sydney]]) to build a fully automated rapid transit system. Several orbital rail schemes have been proposed and some constructed throughout Melbourne's history, but the rail network has remained [[radial route|radial]] with no peripheral connections among the existing railway lines. The [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]] [[Victoria State Government|state government]] led by then-[[Premier of Victoria|Premier]] [[Daniel Andrews]] announced the SRL as infrastructural policy in the lead up to the [[2018 Victorian state election|2018 state election]]. Initial planning for the SRL was carried out in secret prior to its announcement, and, when the plans were released, it received significant attention. The SRL plan has been praised for its long-term vision and ambition, as well as being an innovative solution to the [[traffic congestion|road congestion]]s and [[commuting]] difficulties faced by [[transport in Melbourne|Melbourne's transport network]],<ref name="ArchitectureAU SRL discussion">{{cite news |last1=Stanley |first1=Janet |last2=Stanley |first2=John |title=Melbourne's Suburban Rail Loop: A Big Build or a big bet? |url=https://architectureau.com/articles/melbournes-suburban-rail-loop-a-big-build-or-a-big-bet/ |access-date=7 June 2024 |work=ArchitectureAU |date=18 January 2023 |language=en}}</ref> but is criticised for its political motives, transparency of business case,<ref name="ABC SRL halt">{{cite news |last1=Whitson |first1=Rhiana |last2=Kent |first2=Lucy |title=Calls to halt Suburban Rail Loop project ahead of multi-billion-dollar contract signing |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2023-12-04/calls-scrap-suburban-rail-loop-project-730/103187398 |access-date=7 June 2024 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=4 December 2023 |language=en}}</ref> prioritisation ahead of other transport projects,<ref name="SkyNews SRL review">{{cite news |last1=Huitson |first1=Joseph |title='The time is now': Victorian Opposition calling for Melbourne Airport Rail to be prioritised over Suburban Rail Loop |url=https://www.skynews.com.au/australia-news/politics/the-time-is-now-victorian-opposition-calling-for-melbourne-airport-rail-to-be-priortised-over-suburban-rail-loop/news-story/8a843d1d56d0ed0d0ffce8b04ac0811a |access-date=7 June 2024 |work=Sky News Australia |date=6 July 2023 |language=en}}</ref> and huge cost.<ref name="Guardian SRL cost">{{cite news |last1=Kolovos |first1=Benita |title=Labor won't outline cost of Melbourne's Suburban Rail Loop as opposition cites independent estimates |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2024/mar/13/labor-melbourne-suburban-rail-loop-cost-blowout-claims |access-date=7 June 2024 |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 March 2024 |language=en}}</ref><ref name="AFR SRL cost">{{cite news |last1=McCubbing |first1=Gus |title=Suburban Rail Loop to cost another $16b, Victorian budget office finds |url=https://www.afr.com/politics/suburban-rail-loop-to-cost-another-16b-victorian-budget-office-finds-20240313-p5fc0a |access-date=7 June 2024 |work=[[Australian Financial Review]]|date=13 March 2024 |language=en}}</ref>

Although the Victorian government signed the first $3.6 billion contract with the Suburban Connect consortium in December 2023 to build [[underground tunnel]]s,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Full Steam Ahead For SRL With Major Contract Awarded {{!}} Premier of Victoria |url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/full-steam-ahead-srl-major-contract-awarded |date=12 December 2023 |website=www.premier.vic.gov.au |language=en }}</ref> the [[conservatism in Australia|conservative]] opposition [[Liberal–National Coalition]] remains opposed to the project. Then [[Leader of the Opposition (Victoria)|State Opposition Leader]] [[Brad Battin]] ([[Victorian Liberal Party|Lib]]) announced in January 2025 that he would halt further development of the SRL if he becomes Premier at the [[2026 Victorian state election]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-01-07 |title=Battin vows to scrap electricity commission, names shadow cabinet |url=https://www.afr.com/politics/battin-declares-sec-gone-if-we-win-after-revealing-shadow-cabinet-20250107-p5l2ix |access-date=2025-01-10 |website=Australian Financial Review |language=en}}</ref> [[Leader of the Opposition (Australia)|Federal Opposition Leader]] [[Peter Dutton]] ([[Liberal Party of Australia|Lib]]) and [[Shadow ministry of Peter Dutton|Shadow Infrastructure Minister]] [[Bridget McKenzie]] ([[National Party of Australia|Nat]]) also vowed to scrap $2.2 billion in [[Australian federal budget|federal funding]] for SRL leading up to the [[2025 Australian federal election]], which the Coalition lost in a [[landslide victory|landslide]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-04-01/peter-dutton-coalition-melbourne-airport-rail-link-election-2025/105119666|title=Dutton says Coalition would scrap funding for 'hoax' Suburban Rail Loop in election promise|last=|first=|date=2025-04-01|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=2025-04-20}}</ref> {{As of|September 2025}}, the construction of six SRL East stations is still underway, with [[tunnel boring machine]]s to arrive and start digging in early 2026.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/projects/suburban-rail-loop/construction/tunnelling-works|title=Tunnel works|website=Victoria's Big Build|publisher=[[Victoria State Government]]|accessdate=2025-09-08}}</ref> [[Jess Wilson]] deposed Battin in a [[2025 Liberal Party of Australia (Victorian Division) leadership spill|Liberal leadership spill]] in November 2025, with Wilson reaffirming the party’s opposition to the SRL and committing to halt all development of the project, including current construction, if she becomes Premier at the 2026 election.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Anderson-Byrne |first=Frankie |date=2025-11-20 |title=Suburban Rail Loop pause announced as first policy by new opposition leader |url=https://beat.com.au/suburban-rail-loop-pause-announced-as-first-policy-by-new-opposition-leader/ |access-date=2025-12-11 |website=Beat Magazine |language=en-AU}}</ref>

== Description ==
Upon completion, the Suburban Rail Loop will have three sections: SRL East, North and West.

The first section, '''SRL East''', is a {{cvt|26|km}} underground link from [[Cheltenham, Victoria|Cheltenham]] to [[Box Hill, Victoria|Box Hill]] via [[Monash University]] and [[Deakin University]]. Construction commenced in 2022 with a scheduled opening in 2035.<ref name=":5" />

The second section, '''SRL North''', will be a {{cvt|34|km}} underground extension of SRL East from Box Hill to [[Melbourne Airport]], via [[La Trobe University]]. Construction is not expected to commence until the 2030s, with completion by 2053. This section may be split into two projects due to its length and cost.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 August 2023 |title=SRL North |url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/projects/suburban-rail-loop/srl-north |access-date=24 October 2024 |website=Victoria’s Big Build |language=en}}</ref>

The third section, '''SRL West''', has not been defined in detail but would connect the city's outer western suburbs and may be formed by electrifying the existing [[Deer Park-West Werribee railway line]] from Sunshine and extending it to [[Werribee railway station|Werribee]]. No timeframe for construction has been released.

== Background ==
[[File:Melbourne rail map with former lines and planned extensions.svg|thumb|446x446px|The Suburban Rail Loop, shown with proposed extensions to the Melbourne rail network.]]
{{see also|Railways in Melbourne#History|Transport in Melbourne}}
The Melbourne transport network was substantially developed in the late 19th century, when the newly available technology of the railway enabled population growth away from the city centre. The result was the development of a largely radial network, which, over the following century, reinforced a model of urban development focused on heavy daily commuter flows into and out of the CBD. Furthermore, a program of [[freeway]] construction in the wake of the [[1969 Melbourne Transportation Plan]] reinforced the structure of the suburbs and introduced [[Automobile dependency|car dependence]] to new regions of development not served by the legacy rail network. As a consequence, Melbourne, unlike many cities of comparable size, did not develop any major centres of employment or dense population in its outlying regions over the course of the 20th century.<ref name="Burke 2016">{{cite journal |last1=Burke |first1=Matthew |title=Problems and Prospects for Public Transport Planning in Australian Cities |journal=Built Environment |date=1 March 2016 |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=37–54 |doi=10.2148/benv.42.1.37}}</ref>

A number of orbital lines were constructed at the peak of railway development, but most failed to attract the necessary traffic of passengers and goods to remain sustainable into the late 20th century. The [[Outer Circle railway line|Outer Circle]], which ran from [[Oakleigh railway station|Oakleigh]] on the [[Dandenong railway line|Dandenong line]] to [[Fairfield railway station, Melbourne|Fairfield]] on the [[Hurstbridge railway line|Hurstbridge line]] via the [[Glen Waverley railway line|Glen Waverley]] and [[Lilydale railway line|Lilydale]] lines, was constructed between 1888 and 1891 but closed by 1897, though it was partly reopened as the [[Alamein railway line|Alamein branch line]].<ref name="ABC Outer Circle">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Simon Leo |title=Outer Circle Line film tells of railway 'debacle' |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-15/documentary-on-melbourne-outer-circle-line-to-screen/5967498 |access-date=2 October 2018 |work=ABC News |date=15 December 2014 |language=en-AU |archive-date=26 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826050255/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-15/documentary-on-melbourne-outer-circle-line-to-screen/5967498 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Inner Circle railway line|Inner Circle]] linking the modern-day [[Upfield railway line|Upfield]] and [[Mernda railway line|Mernda]] lines, was opened in 1888 but closed to passengers in 1941.<ref name="Age former orbital lines">{{cite news |last1=Webb |first1=Carolyn |title=Heed the ghosts of Melbourne's railway lines past, says historian |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/heed-the-ghosts-of-melbourne-s-railway-lines-past-says-historian-20180829-p500kc.html |access-date=2 October 2018 |work=[[The Age]]|date=30 August 2018 |language=en |archive-date=6 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906043302/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/heed-the-ghosts-of-melbourne-s-railway-lines-past-says-historian-20180829-p500kc.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Albion-Jacana railway line|Albion-Jacana line]] and [[Newport-Sunshine railway line|Newport-Sunshine line]] in the city's west, though performing a similar purpose, were never intended to carry passenger traffic.

In the late 20th century, interest grew in enabling orbital journeys between Melbourne suburbs. Included in the 1969 Plan were a number of orbital freeways, some of which were constructed over the following decades. The [[M80 Ring Road]] through the outer western and northern suburbs was constructed in stages between 1989 and 1999, and, by the time of its completion, was claimed by its advocates to have been partly responsible for a massive economic boom in the western suburbs, centred on its points of intersection with existing radial routes.<ref name="Age 11 Oct 1999">{{cite news |last1=Hopkins |first1=Phillip |title=A ring road runs through it |work=The Age |date=11 October 1999 |page=4}}</ref>{{efn|This claim has been disputed; well-known public transport advocate [[Paul Mees]] argued that the assertion was "at best premature".<ref name="Mees 2001">{{cite conference |url=http://atrf.info/papers/2001/2001_Mees.pdf |title=The short term effects of Melbourne's Western Ring Road |last1=Mees |first1=Paul |date=2001 |location=Hobart |conference=Australasian Transport Research Forum |access-date=25 October 2018 |archive-date=25 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325082702/http://atrf.info/papers/2001/2001_Mees.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>}} [[EastLink (Melbourne)|EastLink]], a similar orbital freeway through the eastern suburbs, opened in 2008,<ref name="Age 29 Jun 2008">{{cite news |last1=Sexton |first1=Reid |title=Relief as drivers get early start on road of success |work=The Age |date=29 June 2008 |page=4}}</ref> but was less successful, failing to reduce traffic meaningfully on parallel arterials such as [[Springvale Road]].<ref name="HS 19 Aug 2010">{{cite news |last1=Gardiner |first1=Ashley |title=So you hoped Eastlink would make life easier, well think again Springvale Rd traffic jams as bad as ever |work=Herald Sun |date=19 August 2010 |page=10}}</ref> Detailed plans for the [[North East Link]], connecting the Ring Road and EastLink to complete the orbital route, were released in 2018, with construction expected to start in 2020 for an anticipated completion date of 2027.<ref name="Age 9 Sep 2018">{{cite news |last1=Towell |first1=Noel |title=North-East Link: Superhighway through Melbourne's east |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/north-east-route-revealed-20180909-p502nd.html |access-date=25 October 2018 |work=The Age |date=9 September 2018 |language=en |archive-date=26 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026121501/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/north-east-route-revealed-20180909-p502nd.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Despite the investment in orbital road transport from 1990, little changed in the structure of the public transport network. No new suburban railway lines were built after 1930, and trams were increasingly delayed by traffic congestion on key routes.<ref name="Mees & Groenhart 2012">{{cite report |last1=Mees |first1=Paul |last2=Groenhart |first2=Lucy |date=December 2012 |title=Transport Policy at the Crossroads: Travel to work in Australian capital cities 1976–2011 |url=https://apo.org.au/sites/default/files/resource-files/2013-01/apo-nid32490.pdf |publisher=RMIT University |page=21}}</ref> From 2002, the [[SmartBus]] program introduced three orbital bus routes in an attempt to meet the city's burgeoning need for outer suburban public transport. In addition to serving new corridors previously without mass transit, the buses were operated at a relatively high frequency and along direct routes, in contrast to the existing network of infrequent and circuitous routes. As a result, the SmartBus routes became the most heavily used in Melbourne, and were widely praised as a model for recasting the future public transport network.<ref name="Age 27 Oct 2013">{{cite news |last1=Carey |first1=Adam |title=The odyssey |url=http://www.traveller.com.au/the-odyssey-2w8py |access-date=25 October 2018 |work=The Sunday Age |date=27 October 2013 |archive-date=5 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105063411/http://www.traveller.com.au/the-odyssey-2w8py |url-status=live }}</ref>

== History ==
=== Proposal ===
{{Daniel Andrews sidebar}}

In August 2018, three months prior to the [[2018 Victorian state election]], then Premier [[Daniel Andrews]] promised that a re-elected [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor]] government would undertake "the biggest public transport building program in Australian history", in a speech to the [[Committee for Economic Development of Australia]]. The comments were interpreted as a hint that as-yet-unannounced projects would be revealed closer to the election, although Andrews provided no detail in his speech.<ref name="Age 14 Aug 2018">{{cite news |last1=Preiss |first1=Benjamin |title=Victorian Labor promises biggest transport building program in Australia |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/victorian-labor-promises-biggest-transport-building-program-in-australia-20180814-p4zxho.html |access-date=25 October 2018 |work=The Age |date=14 August 2018 |language=en |archive-date=21 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021091659/https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/victorian-labor-promises-biggest-transport-building-program-in-australia-20180814-p4zxho.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 27 August, Andrews revealed plans for the Suburban Rail Loop for the first time: a {{cvt|90|km|mi}} orbital line for Melbourne's rail network, connecting 10 of the city's existing rail lines and serving new regions of the middle and outer suburbs at an estimated cost of $50 billion.<ref name="Age lead 27 Aug 2018">{{cite news |last1=Jacks |first1=Timna |last2=Preiss |first2=Benjamin |title=State government announces massive suburban rail loop for Melbourne |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/state-government-announces-massive-suburban-rail-loop-for-melbourne-20180828-p5005r.html |access-date=25 October 2018 |work=The Age |date=27 August 2018 |language=en |archive-date=5 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105054330/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/state-government-announces-massive-suburban-rail-loop-for-melbourne-20180828-p5005r.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The government committed $300 million to complete a business case and feasibility study should it be re-elected, noting that the project would take several terms of government to complete.<ref name="Australian 28 Aug 2018">{{cite news |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Samantha |last2=Varga |first2=Remy |title=Victoria's Labor government announces $50bn mega rail |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/victorias-labor-government-announces-50bn-mega-rail/news-story/a3838f075d58f770521060cc91228d10 |access-date=25 October 2018 |work=The Australian |date=28 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

In the days following the proposal, the government revealed that its plan had been under consideration within [[Development Victoria]], a planning agency under the [[Department of Environment, Land, Water and Planning]] for 12 months. Controversially, neither [[Infrastructure Victoria]] nor [[Transport for Victoria]], both established by the Andrews government, had been involved in the SRL's planning stages; furthermore, neither agency had identified the need for a similar project in their long-term plans for the transport network. Andrews defended the decision to develop the SRL independently of infrastructure authorities, arguing that while Infrastructure Victoria "have lots of good ideas, they don't have every good idea".<ref name="Age agencies 29 Aug 2018">{{cite news |last1=Carey |first1=Adam |title=Rail pledge makes claim to take politics out of planning sound hollow |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/rail-pledge-makes-claim-to-take-politics-out-of-planning-sound-hollow-20180829-p500jj.html |access-date=25 October 2018 |work=The Age |date=29 August 2018 |language=en |archive-date=20 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920064102/https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/rail-pledge-makes-claim-to-take-politics-out-of-planning-sound-hollow-20180829-p500jj.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

The tender process for the [[Melbourne Airport rail link]] project was launched in mid-September, and the state government confirmed that it anticipated the airport link would form part of the SRL West, with construction beginning in 2022.<ref name="RG 13 Sep 2018">{{cite news |title=Melbourne Airport Rail Link market engagement begins |url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/melbourne-airport-rail-link-market-engagement-begins.html |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=[[Railway Gazette International]]|date=13 September 2018 |language=en |archive-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913144352/https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/melbourne-airport-rail-link-market-engagement-begins.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In mid-October, Labor [[Leader of the Opposition (Australia)|federal Leader of the Opposition]] [[Bill Shorten]] announced support for the SRL, including a commitment for $300 million in initial federal funding should the Labor Party be elected.<ref name="AFR 14 Oct 2018">{{cite news |last1=Durkin |first1=Patrick |title=Shorten, Andrews on unity ticket for $50b rail loop |url=https://www.afr.com/news/politics/bill-shorten-daniel-andrews-on-unity-ticket-for-50b-rail-loop-20181014-h16m1n |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=Australian Financial Review |date=14 October 2018 |archive-date=14 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014080150/https://www.afr.com/news/politics/bill-shorten-daniel-andrews-on-unity-ticket-for-50b-rail-loop-20181014-h16m1n |url-status=live }}</ref> The state government also indicated that it would be prepared to add additional stops to the loop to those included in the original announcement, particularly in the western suburbs.<ref name="9news 14 Oct 218">{{cite news |last1=Lund |first1=Andrew |title=Victorian premier mulls more stations on Suburban Rail Loop |url=https://www.9news.com.au/2018/10/14/19/25/victoria-suburban-rail-loop-more-stations-could-be-added |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=9 News |date=14 October 2018 |archive-date=14 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014120019/https://www.9news.com.au/2018/10/14/19/25/victoria-suburban-rail-loop-more-stations-could-be-added |url-status=live }}</ref>

Days later, a leaked document from Transport for Victoria showed that the SRL had not been included in the transport authority's long-term plan for the rail network.<ref name="Age 16 Oct 2018">{{cite news |last1=Carey |first1=Adam |title=Leaked rail plan shows few extra services for regional commuters |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/leaked-rail-plan-shows-few-extra-services-for-regional-commuters-20181016-p50a0h.html |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=The Age |date=16 October 2018 |language=en |archive-date=24 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124041351/https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/leaked-rail-plan-shows-few-extra-services-for-regional-commuters-20181016-p50a0h.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Planning ===
$300 million was allocated to planning works for the SRL in the 2019 state budget.<ref name="Age 27 May 2019">{{cite news |last1=Jacks |first1=Timna |last2=Lucas |first2=Clay |title=Victoria to write its own ticket for ambitious transport agenda |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/victoria-to-write-its-own-ticket-for-ambitious-transport-agenda-20190527-p51rlk.html |access-date=8 August 2019 |work=The Age |date=27 May 2019 |language=en |archive-date=8 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808015608/https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/victoria-to-write-its-own-ticket-for-ambitious-transport-agenda-20190527-p51rlk.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Rail Projects Victoria announced registrations of interest for potential contractors were open in June,<ref name="RT 16 Jun 2019">{{cite news |title=Victoria opens ROI process for Suburban Rail Loop |url=https://www.railway-technology.com/news/victoria-opens-roi-process-for-suburban-rail-loop/ |access-date=8 August 2019 |work=Railway Technology |date=16 June 2019 |archive-date=8 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808015613/https://www.railway-technology.com/news/victoria-opens-roi-process-for-suburban-rail-loop/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and the first geotechnical investigations began in July in Box Hill.<ref name="Age 23 Jul 2019">{{cite news |last1=Jacks |first1=Timna |title=Suburban Rail Loop work begins as geologists drill deep for $50b line |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/suburban-rail-loop-work-begins-as-geologists-drill-deep-for-50b-line-20190723-p529yw.html |access-date=8 August 2019 |work=The Age |date=23 July 2019 |language=en |archive-date=8 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808015611/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/suburban-rail-loop-work-begins-as-geologists-drill-deep-for-50b-line-20190723-p529yw.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

The state government announced the formation of a Suburban Rail Loop Authority in September, at the same time as confirming station precincts for SRL East.<ref name="Age 3 Sep 2019">{{cite news |last1=Preiss |first1=Benjamin |title=Suburban rail line loops in three big interchanges as route firms up |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/suburban-rail-line-loops-in-three-big-interchanges-as-route-firms-up-20190903-p52nfa.html |access-date=3 September 2019 |work=The Age |date=3 September 2019 |language=en |archive-date=3 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903020536/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/suburban-rail-line-loops-in-three-big-interchanges-as-route-firms-up-20190903-p52nfa.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2019, the government announced that the loop would be an operationally independent, standalone line using different rail technology from the [[Railways in Melbourne|existing suburban rail network]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/new-dedicated-trains-for-standalone-suburban-rail-loop-0/|title=New Dedicated Trains For Standalone Suburban Rail Loop|date=24 November 2019|website=Premier of Victoria|language=en-US|access-date=28 November 2019|archive-date=15 November 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221115153428/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/new-dedicated-trains-for-standalone-suburban-rail-loop-0/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/daniel-andrews-eyes-private-investors-to-fund-suburban-rail-link-20191124-p53dkd.html|title=Daniel Andrews eyes private investors to fund Suburban Rail Link|last=Precel|first=Nicole|date=24 November 2019|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=28 November 2019|archive-date=28 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128033105/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/daniel-andrews-eyes-private-investors-to-fund-suburban-rail-link-20191124-p53dkd.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The system would use new, smaller [[Rapid transit|metro]] rollingstock that is four to five carriages long, allowing shorter platforms.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":0" /> The Premier announced an intention to use private investment to help fund the line, but did not indicate whether the line would be [[Automatic train operation|driverless]].<ref name=":1" />

In 2020, the government committed a further $2.2 billion for initial and early works on the loop, with expressions of interest opened for contractors to deliver these works.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Premier of Victoria |date=16 November 2020 |title=Works To Kick Off On The Suburban Rail Loop |url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/works-kick-suburban-rail-loop |access-date=13 May 2022 |archive-date=14 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221114165754/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/works-kick-suburban-rail-loop |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Jacinta Allan]], who in her role as Minister for Transport Infrastructure had overseen the SRL since its inception, was given the additional role of [[Minister for the Suburban Rail Loop]].

In the 2026 federal budget, the government committed another $3.8 billion to SRL East, bringing total federal funding to $6 billion.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2026-05-11 |title=Could this be the 'most interesting' budget in decades? Here's what we know |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2026-05-12/whats-in-the-budget-here-is-what-we-know-so-far-may-2026/106665572 |access-date=2026-05-12 |work=ABC News |language=en-AU}}</ref>

