The Business and Investment Case of SRL was released in August 2021, primarily focusing on SRL East and North.<ref name=":7">{{cite web |title=Business and Investment Case |url=https://suburbanrailloop.vic.gov.au/Library/BusinessandInvestmentCase |website=Suburban Rail Loop |publisher=Victorian Government |access-date=6 September 2021 |archive-date=6 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210906071727/https://suburbanrailloop.vic.gov.au/Library/BusinessandInvestmentCase |url-status=live }}</ref> SRL East will commence building in 2022 and is expected to finish by 2035. The rail line will be fully underground between Cheltenham and the Airport, while SRL West is subject to further investigation, planning and development.

The business case modelled two staging scenarios. The first scenario has SRL North opening in two sections, the first from Box Hill to Reservoir opening in 2043 and the second between Reservoir and the Airport opening in 2053. This scenario has estimated capital costs of $24.1 to $40.2 billion and total costs of $30.7 to $50.5 billion, with estimated benefits of $48.5 to $58.7 billion.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Suburban Rail Loop Authority |date=August 2021 |title=SRL Business and Investment Case |url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/578281/SRL-Business-and-Investment-Case.pdf |page=308 |access-date=13 May 2022 |archive-date=12 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220312064520/https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/578281/SRL-Business-and-Investment-Case.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> The second scenario is faster but higher cost and has the section from Box Hill to Reservoir opening by 2038 and the full SRL North corridor from Box Hill to the Airport opening by 2043. This scenario had capital costs of $27.1 to $45.1 billion, total costs of $35.1 to $57.6 billion and benefits of $54.7 to $65.8 billion.<ref name=":3" /> The timing and cost would be further refined through the tender and planning process. This gave the project a cost-benefit ratio range between 1.0 and 1.7.

The government stated that it expected $30 to $34.5 billion would be spent on the project over the 14 years to the opening of the first stage in 2035, with significant works on SRL North taking place as part of that expenditure.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Premier of Victoria |date=19 August 2021 |title=Next Steps For Suburban Rail Loop |url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/next-steps-suburban-rail-loop |access-date=13 May 2022 |archive-date=22 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220122004503/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/next-steps-suburban-rail-loop |url-status=live }}</ref>

An Environmental Effects Statement (EES) process for SRL East was initiated in late 2021 that provided more detail on the station locations, the precinct designs, the local effects of the project and the design of the train system.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Suburban Rail Loop Authority |date=November 2021 |title=Suburban Rail Loop Environmental Effects Statement |url=https://srleastees.vic.gov.au/ |access-date=13 May 2022 |website=srleastees.vic.gov.au |archive-date=18 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220518151351/https://srleastees.vic.gov.au/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Community and stakeholder consultation was launched as part of this process.

In October 2021, the Minister for Transport Infrastructure, Jacinta Allan, introduced legislation to the Victorian Parliament to establish the Suburban Rail Loop Authority as a statutory government body and to grant it a number of transport and planning powers.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Suburban Rail Loop Bill 2021 |url=https://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/bills/suburban-rail-loop-bill-2021 |access-date=13 May 2022 |website=www.legislation.vic.gov.au |archive-date=15 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221215022942/https://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/bills/suburban-rail-loop-bill-2021 |url-status=live }}</ref>

SRL East and North will take more than 25 years to construct and together are estimated by the project's business case to cost between $30.7 and $57.6 billion depending on project staging, of which capital costs would be between $24.1 and $45.1 billion,<ref name=":5" /> and will be built entirely [[underground rail|underground]] along new rail alignments.

==Under construction==
===SRL East===
{{main|Suburban Rail Loop East}}
[[File:Aerial view of staging area for Suburban Rail Loop East works in Box Hill Gardens, Melbourne.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of construction for Suburban Rail Loop East in [[Box Hill, Victoria|Box Hill Gardens]] in November 2024.]]
The first stage will connect Melbourne's eastern and south-eastern suburbs, including twin {{Convert|26|km|mi|abbr=on}} underground tunnels from [[Cheltenham, Victoria|Cheltenham]] to [[Box Hill, Victoria|Box Hill]] via [[Monash University]]. Construction commenced in 2022 and is expected to open in 2035.<ref name=":5" /> Passengers will be able to interchange with the existing metropolitan rail network at Cheltenham, Clayton, Glen Waverley and Box Hill. Construction on SRL East began in mid 2022 and the first services are scheduled to start in 2035.

In August 2023, the Suburban Connect consortium consisted of [[CIMIC Group|CPB Contractors]], [[Ghella (company)|Ghella]] and [[Acciona]] was announced as the preferred bidder for the first package of {{convert|16|km|mi|abbr=on}} of SRL East tunnels between Cheltenham and Glen Waverley.<ref name=":12">{{Cite web |date=2023-08-29 |title=Preferred bidder announced for SRL East tunnelling contract |url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/news/suburban-rail-loop/preferred-bidder-announced-for-srl-east-tunnelling-contract |access-date=2023-08-31 |website=Victoria’s Big Build |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":13">{{Cite web |last=Duboudin |first=Tony |date=2023-08-30 |title=Preferred bidder named for Melbourne Suburban Rail Loop tunnelling |url=https://www.railjournal.com/regions/australia-nz/preferred-bidder-named-for-melbourne-suburban-rail-loop-tunnelling/ |access-date=2023-08-31 |website=International Railway Journal |language=en-GB}}</ref>

In December 2025, Victorian Premier [[Jacinta Allan]] announced that taxes would be raised through measures the existing [[land tax]] and windfall gains tax, new infrastructure contribution levies paid by property developers, car park levies, and through state-generated developments.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |access-date=19 December 2025 |url-status=live |archive-date=19 December 2025 |date=18 December 2025 |title=Victorian Government details 'value capture' mechanisms to fund Suburban Rail Loop east |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251219012752/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-12-18/victorian-government-suburban-rail-loop-value-capture/106158982 |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-12-18/victorian-government-suburban-rail-loop-value-capture/106158982}}</ref> The federal government has also promised to contribute $10{{nbsp}}billion in extra funding. The state government also announced that a contract to build the new trains would be awarded to TansitLinX, which is a consortium that consists of [[John Holland Group|John Holland]], [[RATP Dev]], [[Alstom]], KP and [[WSP Global|WSP]].<ref>{{cite news |work=[[Australian Financial Review]] |access-date=19 December 2025 |archive-date=17 December 2025 |url=https://www.afr.com/politics/albanese-government-to-stump-up-10b-for-victorian-rail-loop-20251217-p5noec |archive-url=https://archive.today/20251217105708/https://www.afr.com/politics/albanese-government-to-stump-up-10b-for-victorian-rail-loop-20251217-p5noec |url-status=live |title=Albanese government to stump up $10b for Victorian rail loop |url-access=subscription |date=17 December 2025 |first=Sumeyya |last=Ilanbey}}</ref> The model of the Suburban Rail Loop trains are based on the [[Alstom Metropolis]] family.<ref name=":6"/>

==Proposed extensions==
{{Suburban Rail Loop}}
SRL East and SRL North will form one continuous metro line stretching {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=on}} from Cheltenham to Melbourne Airport. SRL West will be formed by an undetermined project, with [[Melbourne Airport Rail]] on the conventional rail network acting as an interchange link between SRL West and SRL North.

The SRL Strategic Assessment produced by Development Victoria in 2018 identified four distinct sections of the route, some of which are formed by other projects or existing rail corridors. The overall corridor selected was originally identified as a "middle" corridor, and was assessed against other routes closer to and further from the CBD before being prioritised for further investigation.<ref name="DV p22">{{cite book |title=Suburban Rail Loop: Strategic Assessment |date=2018 |publisher=Development Victoria |page=22 |url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/328901/Suburban-Rail-Loop-Strategic-Assessment-.pdf |access-date=3 November 2018 |ref={{sfnref|Development Victoria|2018}} |archive-date=19 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919081754/https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/328901/Suburban-Rail-Loop-Strategic-Assessment-.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== SRL North ===
SRL North between Box Hill station and [[Melbourne Airport]] would be constructed after SRL East, and include stops at [[Doncaster, Victoria|Doncaster]], a middle suburb long proposed for the terminus of a [[Doncaster railway line|new rail line]]; [[Heidelberg railway station|Heidelberg station]] on the [[Hurstbridge railway line|Hurstbridge line]]; [[Reservoir railway station|Reservoir station]] on the [[Mernda railway line|Mernda line]]; [[Bundoora, Victoria|Bundoora]], home to the main campus of [[La Trobe University]]; [[Broadmeadows railway station, Melbourne|Broadmeadows station]] on the [[Craigieburn railway line|Craigieburn line]]; and the airport itself. This section of the SRL would also be constructed entirely underground, and Broadmeadows would function as a "super-hub" for the [[Seymour V/Line rail service|Seymour]] and [[North East railway line|North East]] regional lines.<ref name="PR broady">{{cite news |title=Rail Loop Set To Connect North-East Victoria |url=https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/rail-loop-set-to-connect-north-east-victoria/ |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=Premier of Victoria |date=28 August 2018}}</ref>

The 2021 SRL business case proposed opening SRL North in two stages, the first running from Box Hill to Reservoir and the second between Reservoir and Melbourne Airport.<ref name=":7" />

=== SRL West ===
Apart from the termini at Sunshine and [[Werribee, Victoria|Werribee]], the Strategic Assessment did not identify specific routes, intermediate stations or connections to other lines for SRL West, and suggested it would be the final section constructed.{{sfn|Development Victoria|2018|p=26}} The [[Western Rail Plan]] published by Transport for Victoria in October 2018 suggested that the role of SRL West could be undertaken by [[electrification (rail)|electrifying]] the [[Deer Park - West Werribee railway line|Deer Park – West Werribee line]] to [[Wyndham Vale railway station|Wyndham Vale station]] as an extension of the radial suburban network, and extending the [[Werribee railway line|Werribee line]] to meet it at Wyndham Vale.<ref name="TFV WRP p9">{{cite book |title=Western Rail Plan |date=2018 |publisher=Transport for Victoria |page=9 |url=https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/333705/Western-Rail-Plan.pdf |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-date=7 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307011636/https://bigbuild.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/333705/Western-Rail-Plan.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> Later documents released by the government confirmed that Wyndham Vale would become an interchange station.<ref name="Age 23 Jul 2019" />

== Reception ==
=== Political ===
Following the plan's original announcement, then federal Liberal [[Minister for Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Development|Infrastructure Minister]] [[Alan Tudge]] said that the Suburban Rail Loop's "big vision is great" but said the federal government would withhold its support until further details and costings of the plan were provided.<ref name="Age 28 Aug 2018 costings">{{cite news |last1=Jacks |first1=Timna |last2=Preiss |first2=Benjamin |title=Crucial questions remain over cost of Melbourne's suburban rail loop |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/crucial-questions-remain-over-cost-of-melbourne-s-suburban-rail-loop-20180828-p500cw.html |access-date=5 November 2018 |work=The Age |date=28 August 2018 |language=en |archive-date=5 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105062147/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/crucial-questions-remain-over-cost-of-melbourne-s-suburban-rail-loop-20180828-p500cw.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Then federal Labor leader [[Bill Shorten]] said that he "liked the principle" of the SRL, but would not immediately commit to supporting it with federal funding.<ref name="Age lead 27 Aug 2018" /> He announced federal Labor's official support in mid-October 2018, committing $300 million in business case funding and saying the project responded to an "old map of Melbourne... [that] simply doesn't work any more". His infrastructure spokesman, [[Anthony Albanese]], said that "this project here in Melbourne is the most transformative project for any capital city in Australia".<ref name="AFR 14 Oct 2018" /> Shorten later called the project the "[[Holy Grail]]" of public transport projects.<ref name="New Daily 28 Oct 2018">{{cite news |last1=Eddie |first1=Rachel |title=Victoria election: Daniel Andrews, Matthew Guy launch campaigns |url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/state/vic/2018/10/28/victoria-election-daniel-andrews-matthew-guy-labor-liberals/ |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=The New Daily |date=28 October 2018 |archive-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107091340/https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/state/vic/2018/10/28/victoria-election-daniel-andrews-matthew-guy-labor-liberals/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Then opposition treasury spokesman [[Michael O'Brien (Victorian politician)|Michael O'Brien]] said that the SRL was a "plan for the next election rather than a plan for the next generation", and called on the government to send its plans to Infrastructure Victoria for independent costings and analysis.<ref name="Age lead 27 Aug 2018" /> Despite the Coalition opposing the SRL, the plan was embraced by influential former Liberal premier [[Jeff Kennett]], who called for bipartisan support for the project immediately after it was announced, despite expressing doubts about the accuracy of the $50 billion costing.<ref name="Age 28 Aug 2018 costings" />

At the [[2018 Victorian state election|2018 state election]], the traditionally Liberal-held seats of [[Electoral district of Mount Waverley|Mount Waverley]], [[Electoral district of Burwood|Burwood]] and [[Electoral district of Box Hill|Box Hill]] – all falling along the path of the SRL proposal – were claimed by the Labor Party after large swings, leading to speculation among Labor MPs and electoral commentators that the SRL announcement had contributed significantly to the government being returned with an increased majority. The phenomenon was also replicated in a number of safe Labor seats which would benefit from the line.<ref name="Urban 25 Nov 2018">{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Alistair |title=Did the Suburban Rail Loop win the Victorian election for Labor? |url=https://www.urban.com.au/transport/2018/11/25/did-the-suburban-rail-loop-win-the-victorian-election-for-labor |access-date=2 December 2018 |work=Urban |date=25 November 2018 |language=en-AU |archive-date=2 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202112706/https://www.urban.com.au/transport/2018/11/25/did-the-suburban-rail-loop-win-the-victorian-election-for-labor |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="HS 26 Nov 2018">{{cite news |last1=Johnston |first1=Matt |last2=Dowling |first2=James |title=How ALP rolled the rest |work=Herald Sun |date=26 November 2018 |page=4}}</ref>

In the lead-up to the [[2022 Victorian state election|2022 state election]], then Opposition Leader [[Matthew Guy]] promised to shelve the Suburban Rail Loop if the Coalition was elected, arguing that the project was a waste of money.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sakkal |first=Paul |date=17 August 2022 |title=Matthew Guy says Coalition will shelve 'dreamt up' Suburban Rail Loop |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/matthew-guy-says-coalition-will-dump-suburban-rail-loop-20220817-p5bag7.html |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=The Age |language=en |archive-date=17 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220817073730/https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/matthew-guy-says-coalition-will-dump-suburban-rail-loop-20220817-p5bag7.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Staszewska |first=Ewa |date=17 August 2022 |title='Our state is sick': Guy's promise to fix Victoria's health system |url=https://www.skynews.com.au/australia-news/politics/matthew-guy-pledges-to-scrap-suburban-railway-loop-to-fix-victorias-health-system-in-key-seat-of-caulfield/news-story/7fad86d150da81c10cdbc4649397271d |access-date=29 November 2022 |website=skynews |language=en |archive-date=29 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221129033445/https://www.skynews.com.au/australia-news/politics/matthew-guy-pledges-to-scrap-suburban-railway-loop-to-fix-victorias-health-system-in-key-seat-of-caulfield/news-story/7fad86d150da81c10cdbc4649397271d |url-status=live }}</ref> The SRL became a major and contentious issue during the campaign, with Guy pledging to reallocate the saved money to health infrastructure.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Suburban Rail Loop: Will it be built and do Victorians want it to be? |url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/the-suburban-rail-loop-will-it-be-built-and-do-victorians-want-it-to-be/54fbcc9b-b21b-45bf-96ab-c467a7897c73 |access-date=29 November 2022 |website=www.9news.com.au |date=11 November 2022 |archive-date=29 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221129041651/https://www.9news.com.au/national/the-suburban-rail-loop-will-it-be-built-and-do-victorians-want-it-to-be/54fbcc9b-b21b-45bf-96ab-c467a7897c73 |url-status=live }}</ref> Described by some commentators as a politically risky move in Melbourne's eastern suburbs that would be connected by the line, Guy committed to honour the $2.2 billion early works contract but reappropriate the remaining $9.6 billion allocated to the SRL by the government.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 August 2022 |title=Digging in: Matthew Guy's gamble on scrapping Victoria's suburban rail loop |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2022/aug/18/digging-in-matthew-guys-gamble-on-scrapping-victorias-suburban-rail-loop |access-date=29 November 2022 |website=The Guardian |language=en |archive-date=29 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221129041644/https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2022/aug/18/digging-in-matthew-guys-gamble-on-scrapping-victorias-suburban-rail-loop |url-status=live }}</ref> During the campaign, there was significant debate in the media over the project's cost and value for money.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=McMillan |first1=Clay |last2=Lucas |first2=Ashleigh |date=28 August 2022 |title=Andrews questions inflated costs in Suburban Rail Loop analysis |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/new-analysis-disputes-suburban-rail-loop-value-20220828-p5bd9z.html |access-date=11 January 2023 |website=The Age |language=en |archive-date=11 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230111234736/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/new-analysis-disputes-suburban-rail-loop-value-20220828-p5bd9z.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=21 September 2022 |title=Victoria's auditor general pokes holes in Suburban Rail Loop business case |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2022/sep/21/victorias-auditor-general-pokes-holes-in-suburban-rail-loop-business-case |access-date=11 January 2023 |website=The Guardian |language=en |archive-date=11 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230111234736/https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2022/sep/21/victorias-auditor-general-pokes-holes-in-suburban-rail-loop-business-case |url-status=live }}</ref> After the Labor government won a third term at the election with an increased majority, then Premier [[Daniel Andrews]] said the result was the second clear endorsement of the project by Victorian voters.<ref>{{Cite news |date=26 November 2022 |title=Daniel Andrews says Labor victory confirms Victoria is nation's 'most progressive' state |language=en-AU |work=ABC News |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-11-27/victoria-election-daniel-andrews-labor-win-liberal-party-loss/101703068 |access-date=29 November 2022 |archive-date=28 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221128215121/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-11-27/victoria-election-daniel-andrews-labor-win-liberal-party-loss/101703068 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Delivering For All Victorians With The Suburban Rail Loop {{!}} Premier of Victoria |url=http://www.premier.vic.gov.au/delivering-all-victorians-suburban-rail-loop |access-date=29 November 2022 |website=www.premier.vic.gov.au |language=en |archive-date=29 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221129041653/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/delivering-all-victorians-suburban-rail-loop |url-status=live }}</ref>

As of {{CURRENTYEAR}}, the project remains opposed by the state [[Coalition (Australia)|Liberal/National]] opposition. In January 2025, then-[[Leader of the Opposition (Victoria)|opposition Leader]] [[John Pesutto]] pledged to pause and review the project if the Coalition won government in [[2026 Victorian state election|2026]], citing concerns about large state debt, cost uncertainty, and the lack of funding available for other transport projects.<ref name="Age Pesutto pause">{{cite news |last1=Rooney |first1=Kieran |date=28 January 2024 |title=Pesutto vows to pause and review Suburban Rail Loop |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/pesutto-vows-to-pause-and-review-suburban-rail-loop-20240128-p5f0l8.html |access-date=7 June 2024 |work=The Age |language=en}}</ref>

=== Media ===
''[[The Age]]'', in its editorial the day following the announcement, wrote that "there are so many reasons to endorse this proposal that it’s easy to get carried away", but observed that "good government is ultimately about more than just vision. It’s about having the inventiveness, discipline and fiscal capacity to make that vision reality", and suggested that the true test for the SRL would be the government's ability to complete it.<ref name="Age 28 Aug 2018 editorial">{{cite news |title=Suburban rail loop plan has lots of merit, but let's see the detail |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/suburban-rail-loop-plan-has-lots-of-merit-but-let-s-see-the-detail-20180828-p50091.html |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=The Age |date=28 August 2018 |language=en |archive-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913054636/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/suburban-rail-loop-plan-has-lots-of-merit-but-let-s-see-the-detail-20180828-p50091.html |url-status=live }}</ref> 

''[[Herald Sun]]'' political editor Matt Johnston was less supportive of what he called a "highly political" project, arguing that the comparisons to other major global cities ignored the fact that "Australia is fairly remote, has a relatively small population and has higher labour costs". However, Johnston also noted that "the route of the suburban rail loop... would go near to, or through, Liberal-held state seats such as Mount Waverley and Burwood [and] near to, or through, federal Liberal seats such as Chisholm and Deakin".<ref name="HS 31 Aug 2018 editorial">{{cite news |last1=Johnston |first1=Matt |title=Dan's tunnel is likely to have plenty of twists |work=Herald Sun |date=31 August 2018 |page=55}}</ref>

In subsequent years, The Age has called for the project to be delayed or scrapped due to increasing debt on the Victorian budget.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-05-07 |title=Victoria is driving towards a debt cliff. Here's one way to hit the brakes |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/victoria-is-driving-towards-a-debt-cliff-here-s-one-way-to-hit-the-brakes-20240507-p5fqjh.html |access-date=2024-05-08 |website=The Age |language=en}}</ref>

=== Experts and lobby groups ===
The SRL was warmly received by the [[Public Transport Users Association]], with spokesman [[Daniel Bowen]] describing it as "Big City thinking" in an opinion piece.<ref name="Age 28 Aug 2018 Dan Bowen">{{cite news |last1=Bowen |first1=Daniel |title=This is Big City thinking, and should be applauded |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/this-is-big-city-thinking-and-should-be-applauded-20180828-p5008h.html |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=The Age |date=28 August 2018 |language=en |archive-date=5 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105160538/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/this-is-big-city-thinking-and-should-be-applauded-20180828-p5008h.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Prominent public transport advocate [[Graham Currie]] also supported the plan for its potential to induce new development in the outer suburbs, although he admitted being stunned by the government's secretive planning process.<ref name="ABC 22 Oct 2018" /> The [[Royal Automobile Club of Victoria]] also offered in-principle support, saying that "it makes sense for the state to protect a rail corridor through what is now 'middle Melbourne'", although it also argued that the SRL should not overshadow other improvements to the network such as [[Melbourne Metro 2]].<ref name="RACV position">{{cite news |last1=Jones |first1=Dave |title=Melbourne suburban rail loop analysis |url=https://www.racv.com.au/membership/member-benefits/royalauto/motoring/public-transport/melbourne-suburban-rail-loop-racv-comment.html |access-date=5 November 2018 |work=RoyalAuto |publisher=Royal Automobile Club of Victoria |date=September 2018 |language=en-AU |archive-date=5 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105160600/https://www.racv.com.au/membership/member-benefits/royalauto/motoring/public-transport/melbourne-suburban-rail-loop-racv-comment.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

The SRL plan was criticised by rail lobby group the Rail Futures Institute, who argued that its benefits could be produced by a substantially cheaper network of orbital light rail routes.<ref name="Age 6 Sep 2018 RFI">{{cite news |last1=Jacks |first1=Timna |title=What Melbourne's public transport could look like by 2050, according to the experts |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/what-melbourne-s-public-transport-could-look-like-by-2050-according-to-the-experts-20180906-p5026z.html |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=The Age |date=6 September 2018 |language=en |archive-date=7 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907140036/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/what-melbourne-s-public-transport-could-look-like-by-2050-according-to-the-experts-20180906-p5026z.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Marion Terill of the [[Grattan Institute]] was also critical, saying that travel demand did not warrant the investment required for the SRL.<ref name="ABC 22 Oct 2018" />

=== Public ===
Media outlets reported massive levels of public support after the initial announcement of the plan.<ref name="ABC 22 Oct 2018">{{cite news |title='A generation's worth of spending': Is the $50-billion rail loop a waste of money? |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-22/melbourne-50-billion-dollar-rail-loop-planning-questioned/10385702 |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=ABC News |date=22 October 2018 |language=en-AU |archive-date=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103060558/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-22/melbourne-50-billion-dollar-rail-loop-planning-questioned/10385702 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Age 28 Aug 2018 letters">{{cite news |last1=Koob |first1=Simone Fox |title=Melbourne suburban rail loop: What readers think |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/melbourne-suburban-rail-loop-what-readers-think-20180828-p5006z.html |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=The Age |date=28 August 2018 |language=en |archive-date=6 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906053756/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/melbourne-suburban-rail-loop-what-readers-think-20180828-p5006z.html |url-status=live }}</ref> An impromptu competition organised by ''The Age'' to redesign the Melbourne rail network map to incorporate the SRL received entries from leading cartographers and attracted thousands of public votes in the days after the announcement.<ref name="Age 5 Sep 2018">{{cite news |last1=Booker |first1=Chloe |title=Putting the rail loop on the map: Results in on your favourite design |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/putting-the-rail-loop-on-the-map-results-in-on-your-favourite-design-20180905-p501vc.html |access-date=3 November 2018 |work=The Age |date=5 September 2018 |language=en |archive-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913041706/https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/putting-the-rail-loop-on-the-map-results-in-on-your-favourite-design-20180905-p501vc.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Criticism ==
=== Cost ===
Both the plausibility and practicality of the government's initial headline $50 billion construction cost for the project were the subject of significant commentary at the time of the SRL's original announcement.

Political opponents suggested that the government had wildly understated the cost of the project, with former premier Jeff Kennett calling the figure "irresponsibly and fraudulently inaccurate",<ref name="Age 28 Aug 2018 costings" /> state opposition spokesmen suggesting the cost could be between $50 and $100 billion,<ref name="AFR lead 28 Aug 2018">{{cite news |last1=Potter |first1=Ben |title=Victorian state election: Daniel Andrews floats plan for $50b suburban rail loop |url=https://www.afr.com/news/victorian-state-election-daniel-andrews-floats-plans-for-50b-suburban-rail-loop-20180828-h14lla |access-date=31 December 2018 |work=Australian Financial Review |date=28 August 2018 |language=en |archive-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327001935/https://www.afr.com/news/victorian-state-election-daniel-andrews-floats-plans-for-50b-suburban-rail-loop-20180828-h14lla |url-status=live }}</ref> and federal infrastructure minister Alan Tudge later saying he believed $100–150 billion was a more likely range.<ref name="Age 1 Sep 2018">{{cite news |last1=Koziol |first1=Michael |title=Alan Tudge backs 'a bigger Australia' as he eyes the demon of population policy |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/alan-tudge-backs-a-bigger-australia-as-he-eyes-the-demon-of-population-policy-20180901-p5015x.html |access-date=31 December 2018 |work=The Age |date=1 September 2018 |language=en |archive-date=31 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231093210/https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/alan-tudge-backs-a-bigger-australia-as-he-eyes-the-demon-of-population-policy-20180901-p5015x.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Independent experts agreed that the project was likely to ultimately cost more than the government's claim.<ref name="ABC 22 Oct 2018" /> Prominent transport commentator [[Daniel Bowen]], in a "back of the envelope" analysis, concluded that the government was "close to the mark" but expressed reservations about the accuracy of his estimate.<ref name="DB 7 Sep 2018">{{cite web |last1=Bowen |first1=Daniel |date=7 September 2018 |title=More thoughts on the suburban rail loop (Metro 3?) – Daniel Bowen |url=https://www.danielbowen.com/2018/09/07/suburban-rail-loop-more-thoughts/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231093204/https://www.danielbowen.com/2018/09/07/suburban-rail-loop-more-thoughts/ |archive-date=31 December 2018 |access-date=31 December 2018 |website=danielbowen.com |language=en-AU}}</ref>

Separately, transport planners criticised the promises made by state and federal Labor for a total of $600 million in planning funding. ''The Age'' published comments from an engineer arguing that a "competent" business case could be completed for only $5 million.<ref name="Age 14 Oct 2018">{{cite news |last1=Lucas |first1=Clay |last2=Jacks |first2=Timna |title=Hundreds of millions more to plan rail loop, but not all on board |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/hundreds-of-millions-more-to-plan-rail-loop-but-not-all-on-board-20181014-p509kz.html |access-date=13 January 2019 |work=The Age |date=14 October 2018 |archive-date=12 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112032126/https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/hundreds-of-millions-more-to-plan-rail-loop-but-not-all-on-board-20181014-p509kz.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Some commentary also questioned the capacity of the state to fund the project without severe impacts on its fiscal policy, irrespective of its actual cost.<ref name="Age 14 Oct 2018" />

In 2022, Victoria's Parliamentary Budget Office (PBO) released analysis finding that the total construction and operating costs of SRL East and North together between 2022 and 2085 in 2022 dollars would be $29.214 billion, significantly less than other public estimates.<ref name=":10">{{Cite web |last=Parliamentary Budget Office |first=Victoria |date=27 August 2022 |title=Suburban Rail Loop East and North – Value of continued investment |url=https://pbo.vic.gov.au/response/2945 |access-date=24 February 2023 |website=pbo.vic.gov.au |archive-date=25 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230225000659/https://pbo.vic.gov.au/response/2945 |url-status=live }}</ref> In nominal terms, not adjusted for yearly inflation, the PBO estimated that SRL East would cost $36.5 billion by 2035, but that SRL East and North would together cost $81.7 billion to build when the final section opens in 2053, and $125 billion when including 30 years of asset expenditure and operational costs after opening to 2085.<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 August 2022 |title=Daniel Andrews defends Suburban Rail Loop amid claims it could cost more than double the original estimate |language=en-AU |work=ABC News |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-08-18/budget-analysis-puts-rail-line-project-at-200-billion-dollars/101344828 |access-date=18 August 2022 |archive-date=18 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220818231600/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-08-18/budget-analysis-puts-rail-line-project-at-200-billion-dollars/101344828 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Victorian Parliamentary Budget Office |date=18 August 2022 |title=Advice: Suburban Rail Loop East and North – Building and operating costs |url=https://pbo.vic.gov.au/response/2820 |access-date=18 August 2022 |website=pbo.vic.gov.au |archive-date=17 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220817220038/https://pbo.vic.gov.au/response/2820 |url-status=live }}</ref> The PBO analysis was requested by the State Opposition, and the large headline figure prompted calls in the media for the project to be shelved.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ilanbey |first=Sumeyya |date=18 August 2022 |title='Where is the value for money?': Experts back call to shelve $125b rail loop |url=https://www.watoday.com.au/politics/victoria/where-is-the-value-for-money-experts-back-call-to-shelve-125bn-rail-loop-20220818-p5bb0v.html |access-date=18 August 2022 |website=WAtoday |language=en |archive-date=18 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220818231600/https://www.watoday.com.au/politics/victoria/where-is-the-value-for-money-experts-back-call-to-shelve-125bn-rail-loop-20220818-p5bb0v.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Minister Jacinta Allan dismissed the report, saying the Opposition framed the PBO request in order to obtain a large number, including unadjusted asset renewal expenses over fifty years.<ref>{{Citation |last=Clure |first=Elias |title=Fears that Victoria's suburban rail loop project will have a massive cost blowout |date=8 September 2022 |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-09-08/fears-that-victoria%E2%80%99s-suburban-rail-loop-project/14047828 |publisher=730: ABC News |language=en-AU |access-date=24 February 2023 |archive-date=25 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230225000709/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-09-08/fears-that-victoria%E2%80%99s-suburban-rail-loop-project/14047828 |url-status=live }}</ref> The PBO found that while the SRL would cost $29.214 billion in 2022 dollars, its benefits would be only between $17.757 billion and $21.133 billion, meaning a cost-benefit ratio of between 0.6 and 0.7 using a 7% [[Social discount rate|discount rate]]<ref name=":10" />  (with every $1 of benefit in the future worth roughly $0.5 in present day value)

In March 2025, [[Infrastructure Australia]] released an evaluation of the project's first stage, SRL East, concluding that its costs outweighed its projected benefits. The report found that the benefit-cost ratio had been significantly overstated by the Victorian government and urged greater transparency around the business case. The independent body also criticised the business case for lacking sufficient detail on the full scope of the project, while relying heavily on assumed benefits from future stages that may not be delivered for several decades. It recommended that the government develop an “exit strategy” should future assessments continue to show limited value. The Victorian government, as with previous criticisms of the project, rejected the findings, maintaining its commitment and arguing it would drive long-term economic and population growth. The federal government, which has committed $6 billion to SRL East, stated it is considering the report's findings and that any future funding would be assessed in line with Infrastructure Australia's recommendations.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2026-05-11 |title=Could this be the 'most interesting' budget in decades? Here's what we know |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2026-05-12/whats-in-the-budget-here-is-what-we-know-so-far-may-2026/106665572 |access-date=2026-05-12 |work=ABC News |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2025-03-21 |title=Suburban Rail Loop will cost more than what Victoria budgeted for, report warns |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-03-21/victoria-suburban-rail-loop-report-infrastructure-australia/105082444 |access-date=2025-03-23 |work=ABC News |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2025-03-22 |title=Federal government asks for explanation of Victoria's Suburban Rail Loop funding plan |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-03-22/suburban-rail-loop-federal-government-clare-oneil/105084514 |access-date=2025-03-23 |work=ABC News |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Visontay |first1=Elias |last2=Transport |first2=Elias Visontay |last3=reporter |first3=urban affairs |date=2025-03-21 |title=Victorian government urged to prepare 'exit strategy' for Suburban Rail Loop as report finds benefits 'overstated' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2025/mar/21/victorian-government-urged-to-prepare-exit-strategy-for-suburban-rail-loop-as-report-finds-benefits-overstated |access-date=2025-03-23 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

=== Patronage ===
The Strategic Analysis released by the government in 2018 projects total daily trips on the SRL of 400,000 by 2051, making the line the busiest in Melbourne. It suggests that morning peak would have a 60:40 ratio of clockwise to anticlockwise travel, with the balance reversed in the afternoon peak; by comparison, Melbourne's radial lines operate at a 90:10 ratio.{{sfn|Development Victoria|2018|p=13}}

Independent analysis of the plan by SGS Economics in the weeks following its release broadly supported the Strategic Assessment, noting that if the SRL had been in operation in 2018, a {{cvt|2|km|mi}} catchment around each station would have captured "roughly: 270,600 jobs, 416,100 residents, 212,300 workers, and 112,600 higher education students". It argued that SRL East, consequently, would have served 30,000–50,000 daily trips if in operation in 2018, with the qualification that the level of service provided would need to make travel time competitive with car journeys. However, it concluded that the benefits and potential patronage of the North-East and two western sections were more nebulous, as their impact would depend on the efficiency with which the project was leveraged to create new development.<ref name="Rawsley 2018 patronage">{{cite book|last1=Rawsley|first1=Terry|url=https://www.sgsep.com.au/assets/main/Will-the-50b-suburban-rail-loop-shape-the-Melbourne-we-want.pdf|title=Will the $50b Suburban Rail Loop shape the Melbourne we want?|date=2018|publisher=SGS Economics and Planning|pages=9–10|access-date=13 January 2019|archive-date=27 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227181858/https://www.sgsep.com.au/assets/main/Will-the-50b-suburban-rail-loop-shape-the-Melbourne-we-want.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Politicisation of infrastructure projects ===
The initiation of the project's eastern alignment has faced allegations of being a form of [[pork barrel]] politics, as it strategically aligns with marginal electorates in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]]. Notably, stations along the Suburban Rail Loop (SRL) East, such as [[Burwood, Victoria|Burwood]] and [[Box Hill, Victoria|Box Hill]], are situated within electorates that the [[Victorian Labor Party]] secured in the [[2018 Victorian state election]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=29 August 2018 |title=Daniel Andrews' $50bn rail loop through marginal seats |work=[[The Australian]] |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/daniel-andrews-50bn-rail-loop-through-marginal-seats/news-story/f3cc020344ce0ef60f56dacdfee60d96}}</ref>
Furthermore, reviews conducted by the [[Victorian Ombudsman]] and the Victorian Auditor-General's office in 2023 and 2022, respectively, revealed shortcomings in the project's scrutiny and economic justification. Concerns were raised about the lack of transparency in the project's development and the appointment of ministerial staffers within the [[Victoria State Government]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ore |first=Adeshola |date=2022-09-21 |title=Victoria's auditor general pokes holes in Suburban Rail Loop business case |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2022/sep/21/victorias-auditor-general-pokes-holes-in-suburban-rail-loop-business-case |access-date=2023-12-14 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Kolovos |first1=Benita |date=2023-12-06 |title='Creeping politicisation' in Victoria's public service needs 'urgent attention', ombudsman warns |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/dec/06/creeping-politicisation-in-victoria-public-service-needs-urgent-attention-ombudsman-warns |access-date=2023-12-14 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The Age published an article criticising the SRL being devised by only a few of Daniel Andrews’ trusted insiders rather than through regular government agencies or the bureaucracy.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sakkal |first=Timna Jacks, Chip Le Grand, Paul |date=2021-08-14 |title=Thrown in a loop: How Daniel Andrews' biggest project was cooked up behind closed doors |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/thrown-in-a-loop-how-daniel-andrews-biggest-project-was-cooked-up-behind-closed-doors-20210804-p58fsf.html |access-date=2025-02-13 |website=The Age |language=en}}</ref>

The prioritisation of the SRL has drawn criticism that it has sidelined other infrastructure projects that span through safe electorates for the Labor Party, including the long-delayed [[Melbourne Airport Rail]] and upgrades to roads such as the [[Western Highway (Victoria)|Western Highway.]] Despite these criticisms, the state government has maintained that they are committed to other projects and that the SRL will complement improvements to the transport network in the long-term.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-02-10 |title=Allan government on SRL collision course with federal Labor |url=https://www.afr.com/politics/allan-government-on-srl-collision-course-with-federal-labor-20250210-p5lasq |access-date=2025-02-10 |website=Australian Financial Review |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Sakkal |first=Paul |date=2025-02-10 |title=Federal MPs furious over Allan's Suburban Rail Loop 'blackmail' |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/federal-mps-furious-over-allan-s-suburban-rail-loop-blackmail-20250210-p5laxe.html |access-date=2025-02-10 |website=The Age |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Grand |first=Benjamin Preiss, Chip Le |date=2025-01-25 |title=Labor remains committed to Suburban Rail Loop |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/victoria-remains-committed-to-suburban-rail-loop-amid-more-cash-for-airport-rail-20250125-p5l76e.html |access-date=2025-02-10 |website=The Age |language=en}}</ref>

